    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> The Agricultural Revolution, which began roughly twelve thousand years ago, is usually celebrated as the decisive leap toward civilization and progress. Harari turns that story on its head. Measured by the survival of the species, farming was a runaway success and populations exploded; but measured by the life of any individual human being, the typical farmer worked harder, ate worse, and lived under more anxiety than the foragers who came before. The revolution was less a shrewd human choice than a trap that slowly tightened, one from which there was no return.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> Harari separates the success of the species from the well-being of the individual. Judged by copies of DNA or by total calories, communities that domesticated wheat, rice, and maize won overwhelmingly, with numbers leaping from a few million to tens of millions. But the price was paid in bent backs, slipped discs, and worn joints from hoeing, weeding, hauling water, and carrying stones; in a diet narrowed from varied wild game and plants down to a single staple grain; and in the fatal gamble of betting a whole village on a handful of crops, so that one drought, plague of locusts, or war meant everyone starved together. Foragers, with their scattered and mobile food sources, were actually far more resilient. Crucially, no one decided any of this overnight. It emerged from countless small choices made generation after generation for the sake of a little more food and a few more surviving children, until populations had swollen so much that a return to foraging was impossible and the chains were already locked.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key fact / example:</strong> Harari rewrites the story from wheat's point of view: it was this once-unremarkable wild grass that seduced Sapiens into clearing fields, stooping to tend it, and fighting off its pests, until humans were shackled to the plot of soil. Hence the provocation that we did not domesticate wheat; it domesticated us. Settling down and feeding infants on grain porridge also let women bear children more frequently, driving up numbers and, in turn, deepening dependence on farming. Here too appears the luxury trap: once people grow used to full granaries, houses, and stored surplus, these comforts quickly turn from pleasures into necessities they cannot give up, and humans are devoured by the very conveniences they built.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Progress and happiness are not the same thing. Humans are brilliant at multiplying collective power and numbers, but clumsy at translating that power into individual contentment. Many of the newer, more convenient things we chase today may replay the same script: first a gift, then a shackle.</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: Is there anything in your own life that began as a nice extra but that you now cannot do without? Does it really make you freer, or has it bound you more tightly?</p>`
