    body: `<p><strong>Core claim:</strong> The food surplus produced by farming gave rise to cities, kingdoms, and societies in which tens of thousands of strangers had to live side by side. Yet humans can naturally trust only a small circle of kin and friends, so how do thousands of people who do not know one another coordinate to raise monuments the size of pyramids? Harari's answer is the imagined order: a set of rules and values that everyone shares belief in, even though they exist nowhere in the objective world. This is what upholds every large-scale human society.</p><p><strong>The argument:</strong> Harari stresses that an imagined order is not a lie but an intersubjective reality: as long as enough people believe that money has value, that a king rules by divine right, that laws must be obeyed, those beliefs produce real effects that govern how people build, wage war, pay taxes, and pass judgment. It is so hard to overthrow for three reasons. First, it is embedded in the material world, in city plans, architecture, and dress codes, so that people absorb it through their surroundings. Second, it shapes our very desires, so that even our most private longings are its products. Third, it lives in the web of imagination shared among many minds, so that no single person can topple it alone, because changing it means simultaneously persuading countless others.</p><div class="section-break">◆ ◆ ◆</div><p><strong>Key fact / example:</strong> Harari contrasts two documents that each claim to state universal, natural truth. The Code of Hammurabi, from around the eighteenth century BC, divides society into superior free persons, commoners, and slaves, and declares this hierarchy to be ordained by the gods and beyond question. More than three thousand years later, the American Declaration of Independence proclaims that all men are created equal and hold inalienable rights. Harari calmly points out that, biologically speaking, both are equally fictions: there is no objectively existing hierarchy, equality, or set of rights in the world; these are all concepts collectively imagined by Sapiens. The only difference is which imagining more people accept, and which era it comes to govern.</p><p><strong>Takeaway:</strong> Many of the things we treat as self-evident, such as nations, corporations, human rights, and money, are not fixed facts of nature but products of collective agreement. Recognizing this is not about mocking or tearing them down; it is about understanding that precisely because they are imagined, they can be re-imagined and rewritten.</p><p class="thought-question">🤔 Reflect: Think of the social rule you regard as most self-evident and beyond question. If you set it back inside the frame of this only holds because so many people believe it together, would it still feel just as immovable?</p>`
